    <stitle>POWER STEERING GEAR: TRW/ROSS-TAS 40, 55, 65 AND 85 - DISASSEMBLE - STEERING GEAR</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="31">
        <title>STEERING GEAR</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Put the steering gear in a vise, clamping firmly against the housing mounting flange or
                boss. Input shaft should be horizontal; side cover and valve housing are accessible for disassembly (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500319">Figure 19</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500319" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500319" filename="../figg05/G0500319.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 19. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Do not clamp against body of housing. If mounting boss or flange is not accessible, fabricate
                        and attach a mounting plate to the housing mounting bosses.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Prepare for fluid drainage and unplug hydraulic ports (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500320">Figure 20</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500320" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500320" filename="../figg05/G0500320.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 20. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Rotate the input shaft until the timing mark on the end of the sector shaft is in line with
                the timing mark on the end of the housing. This will position the sector shaft for removal (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500321">Figure 21</hotlnk>and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500322">Figure 22</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500321" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500321" filename="../figg05/G0500321.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 21. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0500322" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500322" filename="../figg05/G0500322.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 22. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove and discard dirt and water seal from the housing trunnion (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500322">Figure 22</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove any paint or corrosion from the exposed area of the sector shaft (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500323">Figure 23</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500323" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500323" filename="../figg05/G0500323.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 23. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Tape the serrations and bolt groove of the sector shaft with one layer of masking tape. The
                tape should not extend onto the sector shaft bearing diameter (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500324">Figure 24</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500324" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500324" filename="../figg05/G0500324.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 24. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the sector shaft adjusting screw jam nut (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500325">Figure 25</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500325" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500325" filename="../figg05/G0500325.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 25. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Be prepared for more fluid drainage and remove the six or eight special bolts from the side
                cover (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500326">Figure 26</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500326" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500326" filename="../figg05/G0500326.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 26. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Be prepared for more fluid drainage and remove the side cover and sector shaft assembly from
                the gear. You may start the shaft and cover assembly removal by tapping the end of the shaft lightly
                with a soft mallet or wooden hammer handle (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500327">Figure 27</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500327" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500327" filename="../figg05/G0500327.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 27. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove and discard the side cover gasket (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500328">Figure 28</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500328" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500328" filename="../figg05/G0500328.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 28. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove and discard the vent plug (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500329">Figure 29</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500329" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500329" filename="../figg05/G0500329.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 29. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Turn sector shaft adjusting screw clockwise through the side cover and pull the sector shaft
                out of the side cover (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500330">Figure 30</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500330" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500330" filename="../figg05/G0500330.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 30. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Clamp the side cover in a vise. Place a standard 5/8 inch or 11/16" -3/8 drive socket in the
                center of the side cover. Pry the seal out with a rolling head pry bar, using the socket for support.
                Discard the seal and remove the socket (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500331">Figure 31</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500331" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500331" filename="../figg05/G0500331.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 31. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Don't damage the bore or DU bushing when removing the seal. TAS85 gears are not equipped with
                        the DU bushing.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect the sector shaft assembly for damaged adjusting screw threads. The retainer must be
                securely staked in place. The adjusting screw must rotate by hand with no perceptible end play (lash) (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500332">Figure 32</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500332" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500332" filename="../figg05/G0500332.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 32. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If equipped, remove relief valve cap, O-ring and two-piece relief valve from the valve
                housing. Discard the O-ring (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500333">Figure 33</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500333" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500333" filename="../figg05/G0500333.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 33. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove and discard the dirt and water seal from the input shaft (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500334">Figure 34</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500334" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500334" filename="../figg05/G0500334.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 34. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use fine grade emery cloth to clean any paint or corrosion from the exposed area of the
                input shaft (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500335">Figure 35</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500335" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500335" filename="../figg05/G0500335.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 35. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the four torx head valve housing bolts (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500336">Figure 36</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500336" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500336" filename="../figg05/G0500336.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 36. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Be prepared for more fluid drainage and remove the rack piston subassembly. Place the
                assembly on a clean cloth. For the TAS85 it may help to rotate the input shaft to move the rack piston
                toward the lower end of the housing. This will force the valve housing to exit the main housing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500337">Figure 37</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500337" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500337" filename="../figg05/G0500337.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 37. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <important>
                    <para>The set position of the poppet seat and sleeve assemblies must not be disturbed if the poppets
                        are not going to be replaced or reset during assembly.
                    </para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove and discard the valve housing seal rings (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500338">Figure 38</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Do not remove the input shaft, valve worm assembly or balls from the rack piston until the
                        ball return guides are removed as damage to the ball guides will occur.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f0500338" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500338" filename="../figg05/G0500338.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 38. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove and discard the two special sealing screws. Remove the ball return cap and cap seal.
                Discard the seal (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500339">Figure 39</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <para>OR</para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Bend down the two tabs (tangs) that are against the hex head bolts. Remove two bolts and the
                clip. Discard the clip (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500340">Figure 40</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500339" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500339" filename="../figg05/G0500339.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 39. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0500340" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500340" filename="../figg05/G0500340.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 40. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Make sure the rack piston is on a cloth so the steel balls that fall out won't roll very
                far. Remove ball return guide halves by carefully inserting a screwdriver between the rack piston and
                guides (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500341">Figure 41</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500341" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500341" filename="../figg05/G0500341.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 41. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Left hand ball return guide halves are copper plated for identification and right hand guides
                        are not plated.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the steel balls from the rack piston by rotating the input shaft valve worm assembly
                until the balls fall out. Place the balls and return guides in a cup or other container. Count the balls
                and make sure all have been removed (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500342">Figure 42</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500342" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500342" filename="../figg05/G0500342.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 42. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The steel balls are a matched set. If any are lost, the set must be replaced by service balls.
                        Number of factory balls installed: TAS40-29, TAS55-31 (30 if date code is 337-89 or earlier),
                        TAS65-32, TAS85-34.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the input shaft, valve/worm, valve housing subassembly from the rack piston (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500343">Figure 43</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500343" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500343" filename="../figg05/G0500343.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 43. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Cut and remove the Teflon seal ring and O-ring from the rack piston (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500344">Figure 44</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500344" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500344" filename="../figg05/G0500344.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 44. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Push poppet stems (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500345">Figure 45</hotlnk>); they should spring back. Push poppet seat; it should not
                move by hand. If components are bent or broken, poppet stems don't spring back, or poppet seat moves by
                hand, go to ,
                <hotlnk document="s05003y_HL0500310.xml" xrefid="hl0500310">POPPET COMPONENT</hotlnk>.
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500345" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500345" filename="../figg05/G0500345.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 45. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>It is recommended that the poppet adjuster seat and sleeve assemblies not be removed unless
                        replacement of poppet components is required.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect valve housing/worm screw subassembly for heat damage or bearing roughness (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500346">Figure 46</hotlnk>). If these conditions are present, or if there was
                excessive internal leakage, or if preload adjustment is required, go to ,
                <hotlnk document="s05003y_HL0500311.xml" xrefid="hl0500311">VALVE HOUSING/WORM SCREW</hotlnk>.
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500346" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500346" filename="../figg05/G0500346.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 46. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the retaining ring that is closest to the output end of the housing trunnion (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500347">Figure 47</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500347" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500347" filename="../figg05/G0500347.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 47. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove and discard dirt seal (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500348">Figure 48</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500348" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500348" filename="../figg05/G0500348.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 48. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Insert a screwdriver into housing bearing bore from the trunnion end and carefully push seal
                and spacer washer out of the other end of the bearing bore without damaging the sealing area of the bore
                or the spacer washer (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500349">Figure 49</hotlnk>). Discard the seal.
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500349" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500349" filename="../figg05/G0500349.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 49. Steering Gear Disassembly</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect the roller bearing in the housing for brinelling or spalling. Inspect retaining ring
                for damage. If replacement of either part is required, refer to
                <hotlnk document="s05003y_HL0500312.xml" xrefid="hl0500312">ROLLER BEARING OR RETAINING RING</hotlnk>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect the following for damage:</para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Poppet fixed stop screw and washer if equipped</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Poppet adjusting screw and sealing nut</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Auto-bleed plug</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Manual bleed screw</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Auxiliary port plugs and O-rings.</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para>If any are damaged, refer to
                <hotlnk document="s05003y_HL0500318.xml" xrefid="hl0500318">HOUSING PORTS, PLUGS AND SCREWS</hotlnk>
                .
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
